<subSubSection lastPageId="4" lastPageNumber="480" pageId="3" pageNumber="479" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,1005,2038]" lastBlockId="4.[151,1436,151,213]" lastPageId="4" lastPageNumber="480" pageId="3" pageNumber="479">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,328,1977,2002]" pageId="3" pageNumber="479">Comments</emphasis>
. This species does not seem closely related to any of the others discussed here. The broad bases to the two terminal antennal segments are unique amongst the 
<taxonomicName box="[854,1041,2013,2037]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Hoplandrothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="479" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[854,1041,2013,2037]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="479">Hoplandrothrips</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species from 
<collectingCountry box="[1208,1313,2013,2038]" name="Australia" pageId="3" pageNumber="479">Australia</collectingCountry>
, the slight separation of the maxillary stylets occurs among these Australian species only in 
<taxonomicName box="[1080,1141,152,176]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Hoplandrothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="480" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ibisci">
<emphasis box="[1080,1141,152,176]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="480">ibisci</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and the presence of only two sensoria on the third antennal segment is also relatively unusual.
</paragraph>
